Good intentions were used to kill and to control and to terrorize the masses [of the people], and also good intentions were used to destroy many buildings, strongholds, and systems of society. We should know, however, that all of those cannot replace a true imam.
Reflecting on this fact and looking at history support the reality that all leaders and states have always had one false imam1, one butcher who executed power. And it will continue like this: it is a question of who is selected to be that, a false imam and butcher, in the next 100 years. This is how Iraq’s politicians and decision-makers are chosen today, and no one seems to realize that this model is wrong.
12 / 39 It is clear that Saddam Hussein was a significant imam for one hundred years, that he perpetrated a different aspect of the imamate, and that he did a great deal to change the country before he was executed by the Americans. Unfortunately and because of the ignorance of the masses, they praised the last imam after plague of tyranny. Actually, many historians argue that all those who came before Saddam were the mass murderers and the dictators of Iraq, rather than it being Saddam.
